Michel Louis Balinski (born October 6, 1933) is an applied mathematician, economist, operations research analyst and political scientist. As an American, educated in the United States, he has lived and worked primarily in the United States and France. He is known for his work in optimization (combinatorial, linear, nonlinear), convex polyhedra, stable matching, and the theory and practice of electoral systems, jury decision, and social choice. He is Directeur de Recherche de classe exceptionnelle (emeritus) of the C.N.R.S. at the Ecole Polytechnique (Paris). He was awarded the John von Neumann Theory Prize by INFORMS in 2013.
